definition.value: An antimicrobial agent that is applied to non-living objects to destroy harmful microorganisms or to inhibit their activity.

A monocarboxylic acid amide that  is lysergamide in which one of the hydrogens attached to the amide nitrogen is substituted by a 1-hydroxypropan-2-yl group (S-configuration). An ergot alkaloid that has a particularly powerful action on the uterus, its maleate (and formerly tartrate) salt is used in the active management of the third stage of labour, and to prevent or treat postpartum of postabortal haemorrhage caused by uterine atony: by maintaining uterine contraction and tone, blood vessels in the uterine wall are compressed and blood flow reduced.
A one-carbon compound that is methane in which the hydrogens have been replaced by three chlorine and one fluorine atom.
Drugs that bind to but do not activate serotonin receptors, thereby blocking the actions of serotonin or serotonergic agonists.
A tetritol that is butane substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 1, 2, 3 and 4.
The conjugate base of diclofenac.
A substance, extract, or preparation for diffusing or imparting an agreeable or attractive smell.
A dioxolane that is 1,3-dioxolane which is substituted at positions 2, 2, and 4 by imidazol-1-ylmethyl, 2,4-dichlorophenyl, and [para-(4-acetylpiperazin-1-yl)phenoxy]methyl groups, respectively.
Compounds of structure RSSR'.
A member of the class of phenylureas that is urea substituted by a 4-chlorophenyl group and a 3,4-dichlorophenyl group at positions 1 and 3 respectively.
An exogenous or endogenous compound which inhibits serine endopeptidases.
A solvent that is composed of polar molecules. Polar solvents can dissolve ionic compounds or ionisable covalent compounds.
A polar solvent that is capable of acting as a hydron (proton) donor.

A solvent with a comparatively high relative permittivity (or dielectric constant), greater than ca. 15, and a sizable permanent dipole moment, that cannot donate suitably labile hydrogen atoms to form strong hydrogen bonds.
Solvent that is capable of acting as a hydron (proton) acceptor.
Self-ionizing solvent possessing both characteristics of Bronsted acids and bases.

Compounds derived from oxoacids RkE(=O)l(OH)m (l =/= 0) by replacing =O by =NR; thus tautomers of amides. In organic chemistry an unspecified imidic acid is generally a carboximidic acid, RC(=NR)(OH).
A carboximidic acid that is the imidic acid tautomer of urea, H2NC(=NH)OH, and its hydrocarbyl derivatives.
An organic heterobicyclic compound that consists of an imidazole ring ortho-fused to a pyridazine ring.
A secondary amino compound that is (1R)-1-(naphthalen-1-yl)ethanamine in which one of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen is substituted by a 3-[3-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl]propyl group.
The simplest member of the class of methanediols that is methane in which two of the hydrogens have been substituted by hydroxy groups.
An EC 2.1.1.* (methyltransferase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of catechol O-methyltransferase (EC 2.1.1.6).
A drug used in the treatment of Parkinson's disease.
A member of the class of benzaldehydes that is vanillin in which the methoxy group is replaced by an ethoxy group.
A member of the class of biphenyls that consists of a biphenyl ring system substituted by a tetrazole ring at an unspecified position.
An agent and endogenous substances that antagonize or inhibit the development of new blood vessels.
A local anesthetic that is used to numb the surface of a body part.
